{
  "card_id": "previous_candle_high_low",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Previous Candle High/Low",
  "aliases": [
    "Previous Candle's High and Low",
    "previous candle's high and low",
    "prior candle high/low",
    "Prior Candle High/Low",
    "前一根k线高/低点",
    "前一根K线高/低点",
    "前一根蜡烛的高/低"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "The high and low of the immediately preceding candle on the current time frame, used as reference levels to frame the next candle's draw on liquidity or to anticipate a reversal based on whether price displaces and closes outside those levels.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the high and low of the candle immediately prior to the current developing candle on the chosen time frame.",
    "If the prior candle closed bullishly or trend is up, the previous candle high is the primary draw on liquidity; if bearish, the previous candle low is the draw.",
    "If the current candle takes the previous candle's high/low but fails to close outside that level, frame a reversal toward the opposite side (previous candle low/high).",
    "If the current candle closes outside the previous candle's high or low (displacement), anticipate continuation and target the next previous candle's high/low in that direction.",
    "When the current candle is an inside bar (no break of prior high or low), assume continuation of the existing trend and look for the previous high or low aligned with that trend.",
    "When both the previous high and low are swept within a single candle, bias is unclear; wait for the next candle's closure before re-framing."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Used to build intraday bias candle-by-candle by deciding whether the next candle is more likely to sweep the prior candle's high or low. A failure to close outside the previous level frames a reversal back toward the opposite extreme; a close outside frames continuation to the next prior candle's extreme. Works most cleanly on the 4-hour chart and becomes noisier on 1-hour, 30-minute, and 15-minute time frames. Should be confirmed on lower time frames before execution.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Expecting the method to be correct every time — the presenter explicitly notes setups will fail and treats it as a probabilistic bias tool only.",
    "Applying it on lower time frames (1H, 30m, 15m) without recognizing the increased noise and frequent range-bound conditions.",
    "Forcing a bias when a single candle sweeps both the previous high and low — this signals no clear directional read and requires waiting.",
    "Ignoring conflicting PD arrays (e.g., a fair value gap below) when the previous candle high/low alone would suggest the opposite direction.",
    "Assuming price always touches the previous candle high/low — sometimes it fails; analysts should not expect 100% accuracy.",
    "Over-relying on the tool in low time frames (e.g., 15m) without additional confirmation.",
    "Neglecting the closing position of the candle — key is whether price closes outside the previous candle high/low; mere touch is insufficient to confirm breakout."
  ],
